symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.AriaProperties
symbols.description: AriaProperties provides ARIA-compliant properties for screen reader software that can be added to any control renderer.

properties.name: label
properties.description: Defines a string value that labels the current element. See the related labelledBy property.

properties.name: labelledBy
properties.description: Identifies one or more elements that label the current element. See the related label and describedBy properties.

properties.name: describedBy
properties.description: Identifies one or more elements that describe the object. See the related labelledBy property.

properties.name: role
properties.description: Identifies the element role.

properties.name: hasPopup
properties.description: Indicates that the element has a popup context menu or a submenu.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilder
symbols.description:
Calculation Builder allows you to perform arithmetic calculations on constants and variables using standard arithmetic operators as well as most common logical operators and functions.
You can customize the sets of variables and functions that are visible in the calculation builder and introduce your own custom functions, as needed.
Arithmetic expressions can be entered using a touch-friendly visual editor or a textual editor that provides autocomplete suggestions for variables and checks the expression syntax as you type.

properties.name: expression
properties.description:
Holds the arithmetic expression.
Use either this property or aggregation Items. Not both.

properties.name: title
properties.description: The title of the calculation builder element.

properties.name: showToolbar
properties.description: Defines whether the toolbar is visible.

properties.name: wrapItemsInExpression
properties.description:
Defines whether the expression should be wrapped inside the calculation builder field.
If set to false, the expression is rearranged into a single scrollable row.

properties.name: layoutType
properties.description:
Defines the layout type used for the calculation builder.
The layout may include a visual editor, a text editor, or both. In addition, you can set the text editor to be read-only.

properties.name: showInputToolbar
properties.description:
Defines whether the input toolbar is visible.
The input toolbar contains operators and functions that can be used in the expression.

properties.name: readOnly
properties.description: Defines whether the control is read-only.

properties.name: allowComparisonOperators
properties.description: Defines whether comparison operators (<, >, <=, >=, =, !=) are allowed.

properties.name: allowLogicalOperators
properties.description: Defines whether logical operators (AND, OR, XOR, NOT) are allowed.

properties.name: allowSuggestions
properties.description: Defines whether autocomplete suggestions are shown when you type. Available only for desktop devices.

properties.name: allowStringConstants
properties.description:
Defines whether string constants are allowed.
If set to true, the calculation builder doesn't validate custom strings as errors.

properties.name: validationMode
properties.description:
Defines when the expression is validated.
  • If set to LiveChange, the input is validated as you type.
  • If set to FocusOut, the input is validated, once you press Enter or Tab.

properties.name: disabledDefaultTokens
properties.description:
Default operators or functions that are disabled. Delimiter for multiple items is ';'.
Example of usage: +;-;sqrt

aggregations.name: items
aggregations.description: Holds the items (operators and operands) to be displayed in the calculation builder.

aggregations.name: variables
aggregations.description: Holds the variables that can be used in the calculation builder.

aggregations.name: functions
aggregations.description: Holds the custom functions that can be used in the calculation builder.

aggregations.name: operators
aggregations.description:
Holds additional operators defined by the application.
These operators are not validated.

aggregations.name: groups
aggregations.description:
Defines groups of variables.
Variables can be organized into multiple groups for better orientation among different types of variables.

events.name: validateFunction
events.description:
This event is fired for each custom function included in the expression.
Custom functions can be defined using {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderFunction} and validated using {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderValidationResult}.

events.name: change
events.description: This event is fired when the order of items changes, or when some items are added or removed.

events.name: afterValidation
events.description: This event is fired after the expression is validated.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderFunction
symbols.description:
A custom function to be used in the calculation builder.
The default functions available for the calculation builder are defined in {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderFunctionType}.

properties.name: key
properties.description:
A key associated with the function. This property is mandatory.
The key is displayed in the text editor area of the calculation builder.

properties.name: label
properties.description:
Label for the function.
The label is displayed in the visual editor of the calculation builder and in the functions menu on the calculation builder's toolbar.

properties.name: description
properties.description:
Description of the function.
The description is displayed in the functions menu on the calculation builder's toolbar. If no description is specified, it is generated automatically based on the key property and the parameters defined in the items aggregation.

properties.name: useDefaultValidation
properties.description:
Defines whether default validation should be used.
Set this property to false to provide your own validation algorithm using {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderValidationResult}.
If you do not provide your own validation algorithm for this custom function, set this property to true, and the function will be validated by the calculation builder.

aggregations.name: items
aggregations.description:
Holds the parameters that can be passed to the function.
For example, if the function has two parameters, the items aggregation may consist of:
  1. A {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderItem} with an empty key for the first argument entered by the user.
  2. A {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderItem} with a "," (comma) key for the comma that separates the arguments.
  3. A {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.CalculationBuilderItem} with an empty key for the second argument entered by the user.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainer
symbols.description: Provides a toolbar with generic functions for tables and charts based on the VizFrame control like zoom, display in fullscreen mode, toggle the legend, switch between chart types, and changes of the chart dimension. The controls of the content aggregation are positioned below the toolbar. Additional functions can be added to the toolbar with the customIcons aggregation.

properties.name: showPersonalization
properties.description: Set to true to display the personalization icon. Set to false to hide it.

properties.name: showFullScreen
properties.description: Set to true to display the full screen icon. Set to false to hide it.

properties.name: fullScreen
properties.description: Display the chart and the toolbar in full screen or normal mode.

properties.name: showLegend
properties.description: Set to true to display the charts' legends. Set to false to hide them. See also showLegendButton.

properties.name: title
properties.description: String shown if there are no dimensions to display.

properties.name: selectorGroupLabel
properties.description: Custom Label for Selectors Group.

deprecated.text: Obsolete property as sap.m.Toolbar is replaced by sap.m.OverflowToolbar.

properties.name: autoAdjustHeight
properties.description: Determine whether to stretch the chart height to the maximum possible height of ChartContainer's parent container. As a prerequisite, the parent container needs to have a fixed value height or be able to determine height from its parent.

properties.name: showZoom
properties.description: Set to true to display zoom icons. Set to false to hide them.

properties.name: showLegendButton
properties.description: Set to true or false to display or hide a button for controlling the visbility of the chart's legend. Please be aware that setting this property to true indirectly is setting showLegend to false. If you need to hide the button but to show the legend, you need to set showLegend at a later point in time (onBeforeRendering). The execution order of the combined properties is not guaranteed by the control.

properties.name: showSelectionDetails
properties.description: Set to true to display the 'Details' button that opens a popup dialog with details about the selected data from the VizFrame based chart.

properties.name: wrapLabels
properties.description: Set to true to wrap text labels in the dialog that opens when the user clicks or taps the 'Details' button.

properties.name: enableScroll
properties.description: If set to true, the Container control has its own scroll bar, with the scrolling taking place within the Container control itself.

aggregations.name: dimensionSelectors
aggregations.description: Dimension Selects.

aggregations.name: content
aggregations.description: ChartToolBar Content aggregation. Only sap.viz.ui5.controls.VizFrame, sap.m.Table and sap.ui.table.Table can be embedded. If not specified explicitly, the rendering order of the charts is determined by the sequence of contents provided by the application via this aggregation. This means, per default the first chart of the aggregation will be rendered within the container.

aggregations.name: toolbar
aggregations.description: Overflow ToolBar. If an external toolbar is used, it will be integrated with the embedded toolbar via a placeholder. This placeholder is mandatory, and it needs to be of type 'sap.suite.ui.commons.ChartContainerToolbarPlaceholder'.

aggregations.name: customIcons
aggregations.description: This aggregation contains the custom icons that should be displayed additionally on the toolbar. It is not guaranteed that the same instance of the sap.ui.core.Icon control will be used within the toolbar, but the toolbar will contain a sap.m.OverflowToolbarButton with an icon property equal to the src property of the sap.ui.core.Icon provided in the aggregation. If a press event is triggered by the icon displayed on the toolbar, then the press handler of the original sap.ui.core.Icon control is used. The instance of the control, that has triggered the press event, can be accessed using the "controlReference" parameter of the event object.

methods.name: getShowLegendButton

returnValue.description: Value of property showLegendButton

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getShowLegendButton showLegendButton}. Set to true or false to display or hide a button for controlling the visbility of the chart's legend. Please be aware that setting this property to true indirectly is setting showLegend to false. If you need to hide the button but to show the legend, you need to set showLegend at a later point in time (onBeforeRendering). The execution order of the combined properties is not guaranteed by the control. Default value is true.

methods.description: Set a date range that increments/decrements one calendar month at a time. The month date range begins on the first day of the month (beginning of the day) and ends on the last day of the month (end of the day).

methods.name: setDateRangeWeek

returnValue.description: this to allow method chaining.

parameters.name: dInitialDate
parameters.description: Any date that falls on the desired week. Start/end dates will be adjusted according to the first day of the week.

parameters.name: oSettings

duration.name: duration
duration.description: The number of days in the range with a minimum of 1 and maximum of 7.

iFirstDayOfWeek.name: iFirstDayOfWeek
iFirstDayOfWeek.description: The starting day for the range. Valid values are 0-6, with 0=Sunday and 6=Saturday.

parameters.description: Settings for the object

methods.description:
Set a date range that steps one week at a time. The starting date is set according to the first day of the week (default is Monday) and the initial date. For example, if the first day of the week is set to Tuesday and the initial date is Wednesday, January 9, 2013, then the starting date will be Tuesday, January 8, 2013.

The last day of the range is calculated by adding (duration - 1) days to the starting date.

methods.name: setDateRangeYear

returnValue.description: this to allow method chaining.

parameters.name: dInitialDate
parameters.description: Any date that falls within the desired year.

methods.description: Set a date range that increments/decrements one calendar year at a time. The year date range begins on the first day of the year (beginning of the day) and ends on the last day of the year (end of the day).

This property is mandatory and must be greater than 0.

This property is mandatory and must be greater than 0.

properties.name: label
properties.description: Defines the label of the CustomSizeItem.

properties.description:
Defines the icon to be displayed in the CustomSizeItem.
If no icon is specified, the default image is used, which is derived from the set width and height.

properties.description:
Specifies whether the width and height properties use relative values (true) or absolute values (false).
When used in the customResizeItems aggregation of an {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.imageeditor.ImageEditorContainer}, width and height are multiplied by the width and height properties of the CustomSizeItem.
When used in the customRectangleCropItems or customEllipseCropItems aggregations of an {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.imageeditor.ImageEditorContainer}, aspect ratio is set to the width and height properties of the CustomSizeItem.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.imageeditor.ImageEditor
symbols.description: Image editor displays an image and provides API and visual controls to edit it.

properties.name: src
properties.description:
Image source.
Can be a file or Blob object, a URL address of the image, a Base64 data URL string, or any other source supported by the <img> HTML tag.

properties.name: customShapeSrc
properties.description:
Image source for the custom shape used in custom shape cropping.
Can be a file or Blob object, a URL address of the image, a Base64 data URL string, or any other source supported by the <img> HTML tag.
Note: In Internet Explorer, customShape doesn't support SVG files and will throw and exception if SVG files are used.

properties.name: mode
properties.description:
Image editor mode.
Four modes are available: resize mode, crop to rectangle mode, crop to circle mode, and display image mode (default).
The default mode displays the image to be edited.

properties.name: keepCropAspectRatio
properties.description: Defines whether aspect ratio should be kept when the crop area is expanded or shrunk in the CropRectangle or CropEllipse modes ({@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ImageEditorMode}).

properties.name: keepResizeAspectRatio
properties.description: Defines whether aspect ratio should be kept when the image is resized in the Resize mode ({@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ImageEditorMode}) or using the {@link #setWidth} or {@link #setHeight} methods.

properties.name: scaleCropArea
properties.description:
Defines the behavior of the crop area when zooming in or out.
If set to true, the crop area is scaled up or down when the zoom level is changed.
If set to false, the crop area remains unchanged and keeps its size.

events.name: loaded
events.description: This event is fired after the image specified in the src property is successfully loaded.

events.name: error
events.description: This event is fired if there is an error loading the image specified in the src property, for example, when the URL is unreachable.

events.name: customShapeLoaded
events.description: This event is fired after the image specified in the customShapeSrc property is successfully loaded.

events.name: customShapeError
events.description: This event is fired if there is an error loading the image specified in the customShapeSrc property, for example, when the URL is unreachable.

events.name: sizeChanged
events.description: This event is fired when the size of the image is changed by the user while in the Resize mode ({@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ImageEditorMode}).

events.name: cropAreaChanged
events.description: This event is fired when the size of the crop area is changed by the user while in the CropRectangle or CropEllipse mode ({@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ImageEditorMode}).

events.name: zoomChanged
events.description: This event is fired when the zoom level is changed by the user interaction.

events.name: historyChanged
events.description:
This event is fired each time there is a change in the history of recent actions or in the recent actions history index.
This may happen either when an action is performed on the image or when the {@link #undo}, {@link #redo}, or {@link #jumpToHistory} methods are called.

parameters.name: sId
parameters.description: ID for the new control, generated automatically if no ID is given

parameters.name: mSettings
parameters.description: Initial settings for the new control

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.imageeditor.ImageEditorContainer
symbols.description:
This control acts as a wrapper around the {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.imageeditor.ImageEditor} control. It provides additional image editing capabilities for the convenience of your users.

Toolbar Customization

There are two ways to customize the toolbar, but they cannot be used together:
  • Use enabledButtons property to select the order and visibility of the buttons provided by the ImageEditorContainer control. You can use the customToolbarControls aggregation to add custom controls that will be rendered in the toolbar.
  • Use the {@link #getToolbar} method together with the {@link #getToolbarIds} method to customize the toolbar as you need.
    The changes made to the toolbar will be kept unless some of the methods from previous approach are used. The previous approach involves rerendering of the toolbar, which causes all changes to be lost. Note: If you use this approach, make sure that you make your changes to the mobile toolbars as well, so that your application can be used on mobile devices.
    There are three mobile toolbars available:
    • The header toolbar that can be customized using the method {@link #getMobileHeaderToolbar} and is intended for custom buttons.
    • The zoom toolbar contains zoom functionality that can be customized using the methods {@link #getMobileZoomToolbar} and {@link #getMobileZoomToolbarIds}.
    • The footer toolbar that usually includes the ImageEditorContainer buttons and can be customized using the methods {@link #getMobileFooterToolbar} and {@link #getMobileFooterToolbarIds}.

properties.name: mode
properties.description:
Image editor container mode.
Three modes are available: transform mode, crop mode, and filter mode (default).
The default mode provides filters for image editing: brightness, contrast, saturation, sepia grayscale, and others.

To display more complex processes and workflows, use {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlow} instead.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.MicroProcessFlowRenderType
symbols.description:
Options that define how the micro process flow should be rendered inside its parent container.
These options can be useful when the width of the parent container does not allow for all nodes in the micro process flow to be displayed on the same line.

properties.name: NoWrap
properties.description:
The micro process flow nodes are not wrapped inside the parent container.
The nodes that do not fit into the width of the parent container are not displayed.

properties.name: Scrolling
properties.description:
Two scrolling icons are added to the parent container, which allows navigation by scrolling through the micro process flow.
Please note that the numbers displayed next to the scrolling icons are not recalculated dynamically when you resize the browser window. If you want them to be recalculated, consider using the ScrollingWithResizer render type instead.

properties.name: ScrollingWithResizer
properties.description:
Two scrolling icons are added to the parent container, with the number indicators updated automatically when you resize the browser window.
This option allows scrolling through the micro process flow, just as the Scrolling option does, but may slightly affect the performance. If using this render type affects your application's performance, consider using the Scrolling render type instead.

properties.name: Wrap
properties.description: The micro process flow nodes are wrapped inside the parent container.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.Graph
symbols.description: The network graph control allows you to display data as a network of nodes connected by lines. The nodes can be circular or rectangular and can be joined into groups. You can define custom attributes for nodes and groups of nodes as well as apply layout algorithms that define the graph's appearance.

properties.name: height
properties.description: The height of the graph. If this property is set to 'auto', the network graph will be resized to fit the height of its content, regardless of the height of the parent control.

properties.name: width
properties.description: The width of the graph. If this property is set to 'auto', the network graph will be resized to fit the width of its content, regardless of the width of the parent control.

properties.name: orientation
properties.description: Orientation of the graph flow. This property is used by layout algorithms.

properties.name: enableZoom
properties.description: If this property is set to false, zoom buttons are hidden, and the mouse wheel can be used for scrolling only.

properties.name: enableWheelZoom
properties.description: If this property is set to false, zooming in or out using the mouse wheel is available only when the Ctrl key is pressed.

properties.name: backgroundImage
properties.description: An image to be rendered on the background.

properties.name: backgroundColor
properties.description: Background color.

properties.name: renderType
properties.description: Nodes rendering type. For optimal performance and usability, it is recommended that you use HTML whenever possible.

properties.name: noData
properties.description:
Set this property to true if you want to notify the user that no data has been loaded.
There is no internal check for data received, so we recommend that you make sure you set it correctly when there is no data received, not just when the application is waiting for data to be retrieved.

properties.name: noDataText
properties.description:
Text displayed when no data is set.
This property takes effect only when the noData property is set to true.

aggregations.name: lines
aggregations.description: Holds the lines to be displayed in the graph.

aggregations.name: nodes
aggregations.description: Holds the nodes to be displayed in the graph.

aggregations.name: groups
aggregations.description: Holds a list of groups used in the graph.

aggregations.name: legend
aggregations.description: A custom legend to be rendered instead of the autogenerated one.

aggregations.name: layoutAlgorithm
aggregations.description: Defines the layout algorithm to be used. If not defined, {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.layout.LayeredLayout} is used.

aggregations.name: statuses
aggregations.description: Holds a collection of custom statuses that can be used to assign custom colors to nodes, lines, and groups of nodes, based on their status.

associations.name: ariaDescribedBy
associations.description: Controls or IDs that describe this control. This association is used by screen reader software.

associations.name: ariaLabelledBy
associations.description: Controls or IDs that label this control. This association is used by screen reader software.

events.description: This event is fired just before the layout computation begins.

Rendering using xlink is much faster, but with larger graphs it may slow down the browser performance. Modify this property with care. properties.name: minWidth
properties.description:
Minimal width of the group (swim lane) for the SwimLanes type of {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.LayoutRenderType}.
If not specified, the width of the group (swim lane) is defined automatically, based on the width of the nodes included in the swim lane.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.layout.ForceDirectedLayout
symbols.description: This algorithm uses the deterministic variant of the force-directed layout algorithm {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.layout.ForceBasedLayout} to arrange the nodes included in the network graph. It can be useful for complex graphs, where {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.layout.LayeredLayout} is not sufficient.

properties.name: optimalDistanceConstant
properties.description: The "C" constant from the optimal distance equation used in the Fruchterman-Reingold Algorithm. See {@link https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309193795_Force-Directed_Graph_Drawing_Algorithm}

properties.name: maxIterations
properties.description: Maximum number of iterations (or cooldown steps) the layouting process will go through.

properties.name: maxTime
properties.description: Maximum time in milliseconds the layouting process will run for.

properties.name: initialTemperature
properties.description: Initial 'temperature' of the system, that controls the step width of the nodes' movements and that decreases, or 'cools down', after each iteration.

properties.name: coolDownStep
properties.description: Specifies how much the 'temperature' decreases after every iteration.

properties.name: staticNodes
properties.description: List of keys of nodes that should ignore cooldown iterations and keep their original positions (x and y coordinates) in the graph.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.layout.LayeredLayout
symbols.description: This algorithm uses the klay.js algorithm to rearrange the graph in grid form. It's suitable for process flows and tree-like graphs. It can be used for almost any graph.

properties.name: nodeSpacing
properties.description: Define a minimal distance on nodes the algorithm will try to keep. The default value is 55. Note that values below 50 are incompatible with presence of groups due to insufficient space for group title bars and space between nodes and their groups' borders.

properties.name: nodePlacement
properties.description: A node placement strategy to use (see {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.NodePlacement}).

properties.name: mergeEdges
properties.description: Determines if all lines should lead to the same place in the node, or if each line should point to a different place.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.LayoutRenderType
symbols.description: Types of layout algorithms that define the visual features and layout of the network graph.

properties.name: Forces
properties.description:
Algorithm that arranges the nodes freely in a force-directed manner, based on the attractive and repulsive forces within the graph.
This layout algorithm ignores node groups, so all nodes appear as standalone nodes not grouped in any way.

properties.name: LayeredWithGroups
properties.description: Algorithm that arranges nodes into layers and ensures support for free-form groups.

properties.name: SwimLanes
properties.description: Algorithm that arranges nodes into swim lanes, which are single-layer groups.

properties.name: TwoColumns
properties.description: Algorithm that supports nested groups, similar to SwimLanes, but arranges them into two columns only: one on the left and one on the right.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.LineArrowOrientation
symbols.description: Direction of the arrow on the connector line.

properties.name: Both
properties.description: The arrows on the line point both ways.

properties.name: ChildOf
properties.description: The arrow points from child to parent.

properties.name: None
properties.description: The arrow is hidden.

properties.name: ParentOf
properties.description: The arrow points from parent to child.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.LineArrowPosition
symbols.description: Position of the arrow on a connector line.

properties.name: End
properties.description: The arrow is placed at the end of the last line segment.

properties.name: Middle
properties.description: The arrow is placed in the middle of the last line segment. If the line has only one segment, the arrow appears in the middle of the line.

properties.name: Start
properties.description: The arrow is placed at the beginning of the first line segment.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.LineType
symbols.description: Type of connector line used in the network graph.

properties.name: Dashed
properties.description: Dashed connector line.

properties.name: Dotted
properties.description: Dotted connector line.

properties.name: Solid
properties.description: Solid connector line.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.Node
symbols.description: Holds information about one node. When changing the size of the node after the graph is rendered, you have to manually invalidate the graph, which causes the layout algorithm to be applied again.

properties.name: headerCheckBoxState
properties.description: Defines if the Header checkbox should be displayed and whether it should be selected or not. By default, the checkbox is hidden. Available only for box nodes.

properties.name: collapsed
properties.description: Defines if the subtree of this node is collapsed. By default, it is expanded.

properties.name: selected
properties.description: Shows if the node is selected. Once the node is selected, its appearance changes slightly to distinguish it from other nodes.

properties.name: group
properties.description: Key of the group where this node is included.

properties.name: key
properties.description: Key of the node. This key is used throughout the DOM to reference this node, mainly in the connector line (Line) elements of the graph.

properties.name: shape
properties.description: Shape of the node. The shape is round by default. To create a rectangular node, set this property to Box.

properties.name: icon
properties.description: An icon associated with the element.

properties.name: statusIcon
properties.description: An additional status icon displayed when the node is collapsed.

properties.name: width
properties.description: Width of the node. If the width is not defined, the node expands, so it can fit the content.

properties.name: height
properties.description: Height of the node. In circular nodes, it determines the circle diameter.

properties.name: maxWidth
properties.description: Maximum width allowed. The auto grow algorithm stops increasing the width at this value.

properties.name: x
properties.description:
The x coordinate of the node. This value must be set after the layout algorithm has finished arranging the graph. It may come from the input data but is not required for most layout algorithms.
Works only for CustomLayout or NoopLayout layout algorithms. Other layout algorithms override this property. However, you can still change it using an afterLayouting event.

properties.name: y
properties.description:
The y coordinate of the node. This value must be set after the layout algorithm has finished arranging the graph. It may come from the input data but is not required for most layout algorithms.
Works only for CustomLayout or NoopLayout layout algorithms. Other layout algorithms override this property. However, you can still change it using an afterLayouting event.

properties.name: showExpandButton
properties.description: Determines if the expand button is visible.

properties.name: showActionLinksButton
properties.description: Determines if the links button is visible.

properties.name: showDetailButton
properties.description: Determines if the details button is visible.

properties.name: titleLineSize
properties.description: Determines the maximum number of lines allowed for the node's label. If set to 0, the label may have an unlimited number of lines.

properties.name: descriptionLineSize
properties.description: Determines the maximum number of lines allowed to be displayed in the node's description. If you want to hide the description, set this property to -1 (default). To display an unlimited number of lines, set this property to 0. This property does not affect the description that appears in the tooltip, which is always fully rendered.

properties.name: iconSize
properties.description: Determines the size of the node's icon. This property can be applied only to circular nodes.

properties.name: coreNodeSize
properties.description:
Determines the size of a custom node, which can be useful for nodes that have text or other content outside of its shape.
This property is available for custom nodes only.

properties.name: visible
properties.description: Whether the control should be visible on the screen. Node is still used for layouter.

aggregations.name: actionLinks
aggregations.description: A list of links to be shown in the links area. A link may point to any UI5 control. It's up to the caller to set up all necessary callback functions.

aggregations.name: actionButtons
aggregations.description: A list of custom action buttons. These buttons are displayed in the button area for each node. A node may have up to 4 buttons. The default 3 buttons (collapse/expand, details, and links) have priority over any other custom buttons that you add. If you want all 4 of your custom buttons to be displayed, set the visibility of the default buttons to false.

aggregations.name: image
aggregations.description: The image that is displayed in the node's header instead of the icon.

aggregations.name: content
aggregations.description: Custom content rendered with the node. Available only for rectangular nodes with HTML rendering type. When this aggregation is used, the description and attributes of {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.ElementBase} are ignored.

aggregations.name: _checkBox
aggregations.description: Internal aggregation for the Header checkbox.

methods.name: getWidth

returnValue.description: Value of property width

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getWidth width}. Width of the node. If the width is not defined, the node expands, so it can fit the content. Default value is undefined.

methods.name: getX

returnValue.description: Value of property x

methods.description:
Gets current value of property {@link #getX x}. The x coordinate of the node. This value must be set after the layout algorithm has finished arranging the graph. It may come from the input data but is not required for most layout algorithms.
Works only for CustomLayout or NoopLayout layout algorithms. Other layout algorithms override this property. However, you can still change it using an afterLayouting event. Default value is 0.

methods.name: getY

returnValue.description: Value of property y

methods.description:
Gets current value of property {@link #getY y}. The y coordinate of the node. This value must be set after the layout algorithm has finished arranging the graph. It may come from the input data but is not required for most layout algorithms.
Works only for CustomLayout or NoopLayout layout algorithms. Other layout algorithms override this property. However, you can still change it using an afterLayouting event. Default value is 0.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.Status
symbols.description:
The status element holds information about a custom status that can be applied to nodes, lines, and groups of nodes.

You can create multiple custom statuses and assign them to your graph using the statuses aggregation of the {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.Graph} control.

Alternatively, you can use default statuses provided by the {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.ElementStatus} element.

properties.name: title
properties.description:
Title of the node.
The title that is applied to elements that are in this custom status. The title is displayed in the legend.

properties.name: borderColor
properties.description:
Border color.
The border color that is applied to elements in this custom status.

properties.name: backgroundColor
properties.description:
Fill color.
The fill color that is applied to elements and lines that are in this custom status.

properties.name: contentColor
properties.description:
Color of the content (text or icon) inside the node.
The color is applied to a node's content when it enters this custom status.

properties.name: headerContentColor
properties.description:
Color of the header content (title and icon) of the node.
Applicable only to the rectangular nodes.

properties.name: hoverBackgroundColor
properties.description:
Fill color on hover.
The fill color of a custom status element, line, or group when you hover over it.

properties.name: hoverBorderColor
properties.description:
Border color on hover.
The border color of a custom status element when you hover over it.

properties.name: hoverContentColor
properties.description: Content color on hover. Color of the content (text or icon) inside the custom status element when you hover over it.

properties.name: selectedBackgroundColor
properties.description:
Fill color when selected.
The fill color of a custom status element when you select it.

properties.name: selectedBorderColor
properties.description: Border color when selected. The border color of a custom status element when you select it.

properties.name: selectedContentColor
properties.description: Content color when selected. Color of the content (text or icon) inside the custom status node when you select it.

properties.name: legendColor
properties.description:
Color displayed in the graph's legend.
If not set, the fill color defined in the backgroundColor property is used.

properties.name: useFocusColorAsContentColor
properties.description:
Defines whether the focus border should match the color of the content in focus. If false, the focus border has the default color.
This property can be used only for nodes and groups of nodes.

properties.name: borderWidth
properties.description: Border width of the element in specific units (for example 2px).

properties.name: borderStyle
properties.description: Style of the border. For {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.Line} elements use this value as parameter for stroke-dasharray.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.networkgraph.util.Dijkstra
symbols.description: This algorithm uses Dijkstra's algorithm to compute the shortest possible paths from the starting point node to all other nodes in the graph and arrange them accordingly.

parameters.name: oGraph
parameters.description: Graph to compute the paths in.

parameters.name: oSourceNode
parameters.description: Node that serves as the starting point for computing the paths.

parameters.name: oSettings

fnLineValue.name: fnLineValue
fnLineValue.description: Evaluation function for determining the value of a line. The function will receive the line to be evaluated as a parameter and must return a positive number representing its value (note that Dijkstra's algorithm cannot be used on negative values of lines). If this function is not passed as a parameter, the algorithm will consider the value of each line to be 1.

bIgnoreDirections.name: bIgnoreDirections
bIgnoreDirections.description: Makes the algorithm ignore line directions and treat the graph as non-oriented.

bIgnoreCollapsed.name: bIgnoreCollapsed
bIgnoreCollapsed.description: Makes the algorithm ignore collapsed and hidden nodes.

parameters.description: Settings for the algorithm.

constructor.description: Constructor for a new Dijkstra's algorithm. The constructor computes the shortest paths to all nodes in the network graph from given starting point node.

methods.name: getShortestPathTo

returnValue.description: Lines representing the shortest path.

parameters.name: oToNode
parameters.description: Node to find shortest path to.

methods.description: Retrieves the shortest path to the given node. Due to the nature of the algorithm, the path is returned in reversed order. In most cases, each line has to be processed anyway, so the order is not important. However, if you need to retrieve lines in the direct order, you can use the Array.reverse() method.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlow
symbols.description: Complex control that enables you to display documents or other items in their flow.

properties.name: foldedCorners
properties.description: This property defines the folded corners for the single node control. The following values exist: - true: means folded corner - false/null/undefined: means normal corner

properties.name: scrollable
properties.description:
By default, the control body is embedded into a scroll container of fixed size, so the user can put the control into a fixed size layout. When the control body (the graph) gets larger, the container cuts the overflowing parts of the graph and the cut parts can be displayed by scrolling the control body. When the control body fits into the container limits, obviously no scrolling is possible (and makes sense).

The scrolling feature can be turned off by setting this property value to false, so the width/height of the whole control will change as the flow graph gets smaller/larger. In this case the control body could not be scrolled, as the control body size matches the control container size.

properties.name: wheelZoomable
properties.description: Defines if semantic zooming by mouse wheel events on desktop browsers is enabled.

properties.name: showLabels
properties.description: Defines if the connection labels are shown or not.

returnValue.description: Value of property scrollable

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getScrollable scrollable}. By default, the control body is embedded into a scroll container of fixed size, so the user can put the control into a fixed size layout. When the control body (the graph) gets larger, the container cuts the overflowing parts of the graph and the cut parts can be displayed by scrolling the control body. When the control body fits into the container limits, obviously no scrolling is possible (and makes sense). The scrolling feature can be turned off by setting this property value to false, so the width/height of the whole control will change as the flow graph gets smaller/larger. In this case the control body could not be scrolled, as the control body size matches the control container size. Default value is true.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowConnection
symbols.description: This control is used inside the ProcessFlow control to connect process flow node A with process flow node B in respect to the style(x) chosen by the application.

properties.name: drawData
properties.description: This is an array of the following attributes for one element: 1. flowLine (string) - A connection definition where the line should be drawn. A string which defines a course of a flow line. A flow line is a connection between nodes in a process flow control. The string can contain the following characters: - "r" for right, - "t" for top, - "l" for left, - "b" for bottom. 2. targetNodeState (ProcessFlowNodeState) - A copy of the target node status. If the target node is created, the line is solid. If the target node is planned, the line is dashed. 3. displayState (ProcessFlowDisplayState) - Display state of the node. This property defines if the node is displayed regularly, highlighted, or dimmed in combination with a selected visual style of the control. 4. hasArrow (boolean) - Indicates if the line has an arrow on the right end.

properties.name: zoomLevel
properties.description: This is a current zoom level for the connection. The point of connection to the node is derived from zoom level.

properties.name: type
properties.description: Type of the connection.

deprecated.text: Type is deprecated because of no usages. There will be no replacement.

properties.name: state
properties.description: State of the connection.

deprecated.text: State is deprecated because of no usages. There will be no replacement.

properties.name: priority
properties.description: Priority is used to define which label is visible if the state of multiple labels is equal. Assuming there are multiple labels with equal state (e.g. Negative state appears twice), the priority decides which one needs to be selected.

properties.description: Specifies the state of the connection label. If multiple labels are available for one connection, the label will be selected by state based on the following order: Neutral -> Positive -> Critical -> Negative.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowLaneHeader
symbols.description: This control gives you an overview of documents or items used in a process flow. The process flow is represented by donut chart sections that are colored according to the status of documents. This control can be used in two different ways. If you use it standalone, an event is triggered and can be caught to display the node map. If you use it with nodes or documents, it gives you an overview of the documents or items used in the process flow, which is represented by the donut chart sections.

The user can explicitly set an array with the two properties state and value of the state, for example [state:sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowNodeState.Neutral, value: 20]. Possible states are states are positive, negative, neutral, and planned.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowLaneState
symbols.description: This type is used in the 'state' property of the ProcessFlowLaneHeader. For example, app developers can set the status of the lane header if lanes are displayed without documents. If the complete process flow is displayed (that is, if the lane header is displayed with documents underneath), the given state values of the lane header are ignored and will be calculated in the ProcessFlow according to the current state of the documents.

properties.name: state
properties.description: The 'state' property is associated with the given value. Possible states are: positive, negative, neutral, and planned.

properties.name: value
properties.description: In the 'state' array, the total amount of values needs to be 100%.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowNode
symbols.description: This control enables you to see documents (or other items) in respect to their statuses  positive, negative, neutral, planned, planned negative. In addition to the node title (which can be optionally a hyperlink) also two other text fields are provided and can be filled. The process flow nodes consider all styles depending on the status they are in. The user can update or change the content of the node. The content of the node can be also filtered according to updated data and specific parameters set. This means that also the nodes style is affected.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowNodeState
symbols.description: Describes the state connected to the content it is representing in the Process Flow Node. The state is also displayed in the Process Flow Lane Header as a color segment of the donut.

properties.name: Critical
properties.description: Critical status for a created document: with this document, a critical issue occurred, for example, the business process can be interrupted.

properties.name: Negative
properties.description: Negative status for a created document: with this document, an issue occurred.

properties.name: Neutral
properties.description: Neutral status for a created document: the document is in progress.

properties.name: Planned
properties.description: Planned status for a document: the document is planned to be started.

properties.name: PlannedNegative
properties.description: Planned, but negative status for a document: the planned document has an issue but has not yet been started.

properties.name: Positive
properties.description: Positive status for a created document: the document is done, finished, solved.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowNodeType
symbols.description: Describes the type of a node. The type value could be single or aggregated. With this type, the application can define if several nodes should be displayed as one aggregated node in a path per column to represent a grouping of semantically equal nodes.

properties.name: Aggregated
properties.description: Aggregated node - several nodes are illustrated as a stack of nodes in the same path and in one column.

properties.name: Single
properties.description: Single node - one node is illustrated in a column.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ProcessFlowZoomLevel
symbols.description: The zoom level defines level of details for the node and how much space the process flow requires.

properties.name: Four
properties.description: Zoom level for least details - only icon is displayed.

properties.name: One
properties.description: The full details with normal font size.

properties.name: Three
properties.description: The details are the icon, title text and no additional texts.

properties.name: Two
properties.description: The full detail view of the node but with smaller font size.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.RepeaterViewConfiguration
symbols.description: A configuration control defining how the content of the sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater control is displayed and what data is bound.

deprecated.text: Deprecated. Standard Fiori technology should be used.

properties.name: title
properties.description: The title of the view to be displayed in sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater view selector. If neither this nor "icon" property are defined, the default title "View ##" will be shown, where ## is an index number of the view in View Repeater starting from 1.

properties.name: icon
properties.description: A path to the icon representing this view in sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater view selector.

properties.name: iconHovered
properties.description: A path to the icon representing this view in sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater view selector when the regular icon is hovered.

properties.name: path
properties.description: A path used for rows/titles data binding.

properties.name: itemMinWidth
properties.description: The minimal width of the tile in this view. Only applicable if "responsive" property is set to true.

properties.name: numberOfTiles
properties.description: The number of tiles/rows that will be shown on a single page in this view.

properties.name: responsive
properties.description: This parameter indicates whether the content is shown in rows or tiles. If false, the content is shown in rows just like in core sap.ui.commons.RowRepeater. If true, the content is shown in tiles (similar to sap.ui.ux3.DataSet control) that have minimal width defined by the "itemMinWidth" property. The number of columns depends on the parent control's width. If you resize the control, the number of columns may change respectively so that the content tiles can fill the entire space of a row.

properties.name: external
properties.description: Indicates if the external representation of this view is rendered instead of the row repeater's own content.

properties.name: iconSelected
properties.description: A path to the icon representing this view in sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater view selector when the regular icon is selected.

properties.name: itemHeight
properties.description: The height of the tile in this view in pixels. Only applicable if the responsive property is set to true. This value is used for calculating the number of tile rows.

aggregations.name: template
aggregations.description: The control used as a template while displaying rows/tiles in this view. It should not have fixed width wider than defined by the "itemMinWidth" property, otherwise some content may appear cropped.

aggregations.name: externalRepresentation
aggregations.description: The control to be rendered instead of sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater's own content. Only used if the "external" property is set to true. This allows you to create custom views, for example, Table views. The sap.suite.ui.commons.ViewRepeater control will share its model with this control if the control does not have its own model.

parameters.name: sId
parameters.description: id for the new control, generated automatically if no id is given

parameters.name: mSettings
parameters.description: initial settings for the new control

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.SplitButton
symbols.description: The Split Button Control is a composite control that consists of a default-action Button and a Menu Button control. The default-action button control represents a simple push button. It is used for initiating actions, such as save or print. It can contain some text, an icon, or both; the order of the two can be configured. The action initiated by this button is considered to be the default action for the control, and it must be one of the selections defined in the Menu Button menu. The Menu Button control is a button that opens a menu upon user's click. MenuButton is a composition of the Menu control and the Button control and thus inheriting all features. When a menu item is selected by the user, MenuButton throws an event called itemSelected. The event transfers the itemId of the selected item. As an alternative, the button press event can be used which has a similar behavior.

deprecated.text: Deprecated. Not Fiori.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.statusindicator.FillingOption
symbols.description: Filling options for an SVG shape included in a custom shape.

properties.name: shapeId
properties.description: ID of the fillable SVG shape included in a custom shape.

properties.name: weight
properties.description:
Weight of the fillable shape, relative to other fillable shapes included in this custom shape. This property allows you to distribute the status indicator's value between distinct SVG shapes included in the custom shape. For example, for four SVG shapes with weights 1, 2, 3, and 4 (total weight 10), the status indicator's value is distributed in the following way:
  • If the status indicator's value is below 10% (1 out of 10), the first SVG shape (weight 1) is partially filled, depending on the percentage value. For example, if the percentage value of the status indicator is 5, the first SVG shape appears half-full. The rest of the SVG shapes appear empty.
  • If the status indicator's value is at least 10% but below 30%, the first SVG shape (weight 1) is filled, and the second shape (weight 2) is filled only partially, depending on the percentage value. The rest of the SVG shapes in this custom shape appear empty.
  • If the status indicator's value is at least 30% but below 60%, the first two SVG shapes (weight 1 and 2) are filled, and the third SVG shape (weight 3) is filled only partially. The fourth SVG shape (weight 4) appears empty.
  • If the status indicator's value is at least 60% but below 100%, the first three SVG shapes (weight 1, 2, and 3) are filled, but the fourth SVG shape is filled only partially, depending on the percentage value.
  • If the status indicator's value is 100, all four SVG shapes appear filled.

properties.name: order
properties.description: Order in which this fillable SVG shape must be filled, relative to other SVG shapes included in the custom shape. For example, if you have three SVG shapes with order values 1, 2, and 4 assigned, the first shape will be filled first, then the second shape, and, finally, the third shape, regardless of their order in the SVG definition. The value of this property must be unique.

parameters.name: sId
parameters.description: id for the new control, generated automatically if no id is given

parameters.name: mSettings
parameters.description: initial settings for the new control

constructor.description: Constructor for a new FillingOption. Accepts an object literal mSettings that defines initial property values, aggregated and associated objects as well as event handlers. symbols.description: Abstract shape that displays the value of the status indicator. The shape reflects the status indicator's percentage value by filling one or more of its parts (SVG shapes) with the specified color.

properties.name: fullAnimationDuration
properties.description: Specifies the duration, in milliseconds, of the animation that would fill an empty shape to the full. The actual time it takes to change the shape's filling is proportional to the difference between the initial and the target status indicator's value. For example, a change from 20 percent to 70 percent takes only half of the time specified in the fullAnimationDuration property. If this property is set to 0, changes are applied instantly without any animation.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.statusindicator.ShapeGroup
symbols.description: Group of shapes that display status indicator value. Shapes in the group are filled in parallel, actual animation might depend on particular shape setting.

properties.name: weight
properties.description:
Weight of the group, relative to other groups in the status indicator. This property allows you to distribute the status indicator's value between groups of shapes that it contains. For example, for three groups with weights 10, 10, and 20 (total weight 40), the status indicator's value is distributed in the following way:
  • If the status indicator's value is below 25% (10 out of 40), the first group of shapes (weight 10) is partially filled, depending on the percentage value. For example, if the percentage value is 5, the first group of shapes is 1/5-full. The second and the third groups are empty.
  • If the status indicator's value is at least 25% but below 50%, the first group of shapes (weight 10) is filled, the second group (also weight 10) is partially filled, and the third group (weight 20) appears empty.
  • If the status indicator's value is at least 50% but below 100%, the first two groups of shapes (weight 10 each) are filled, but the third group (weight 20) is only partially filled.
  • If the status indicator's value is 100, all three groups of shapes are filled.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.statusindicator.StatusIndicator
symbols.description: The status indicator control displays a value between 0 and 100. A status indicator may consist of multiple groups that gradually display the value. The shapes in the first group are filled first, the shapes in the second group second, and so on. The value of the status indicator is distributed between the groups depending on their weight. The filling of the shapes in the groups can be proportional to the value of the status indicator or can be based on thresholds specified in the discreteThresholds aggregation.

properties.name: width
properties.description: Width of the status indicator. Only sets the width of the image part of the status indicator, potential label is not included. The root div of the status indicator is set as display: "block" and so takes up the whole space available. Wrap status indicator in {@link sap.m.FlexBox} control if you wish to control width of the whole status indicator.

properties.name: height
properties.description: Height of the status indicator. Only sets the height of the image part of the status indicator, potential label is not included.

properties.name: value
properties.description: Percentage value, between 0 and 100, that the status indicator reflects.

properties.name: viewBox
properties.description: Defines the view box surrounding the shapes included in the status indicator.

properties.name: ariaLabel
properties.description: ARIA label for this control to be used by screen reader software.

properties.name: size
properties.description: Predefined sizes for the status indicator.

aggregations.name: groups
aggregations.description: Groups of shapes that display the status indicator's percentage value. A status indicator must always include at least one group.

aggregations.name: propertyThresholds
aggregations.description: Defines how shapes are filled based on the status indicator's percentage value.

aggregations.name: discreteThresholds
aggregations.description:
Specifies discrete thresholds for the status indicator. If discrete thresholds are set, the status indicator adjusts its appearance to the closest threshold value that is not greater than the actual percentage value of the status indicator. For example, if the following discrete thresholds are specified:
  • value = "20"
  • value = "60"
  • value = "100"
The status indicator displays the following percentage values:
  • 0 if the actual value is 15
  • 20 if the actual value is 20
  • 20 if the actual value is 55
  • 60 if the actual value is 60
  • 60 if the actual value is 79
  • 100 if the actual value is 100
Please note that these thresholds affect only the appearance of the status inicator, not its stored value.

associations.name: ariaLabelledBy
associations.description: Controls or IDs that label this control. Can be used by screen reader software.

methods.name: getDiscreteThresholds
methods.description:
Gets content of aggregation {@link #getDiscreteThresholds discreteThresholds}. Specifies discrete thresholds for the status indicator. If discrete thresholds are set, the status indicator adjusts its appearance to the closest threshold value that is not greater than the actual percentage value of the status indicator. For example, if the following discrete thresholds are specified:
  • value = "20"
  • value = "60"
  • value = "100"
The status indicator displays the following percentage values:
  • 0 if the actual value is 15
  • 20 if the actual value is 20
  • 20 if the actual value is 55
  • 60 if the actual value is 60
  • 60 if the actual value is 79
  • 100 if the actual value is 100
Please note that these thresholds affect only the appearance of the status inicator, not its stored value.

methods.description:
Gets the sum of transactions in all T-account groups included in the panel.
Returns a sum object that is structured as follows:
{
measure: {string} Unit of measurement of the T accounts. If T accounts use different units of measurements, the last one is returned.
sum: {number} Sum of all entries in the T accounts and T-account groups included in the panel.
correct: {boolean} If false, the sum cannot be calculated, because the T accounts use different units of measurement.
}

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.ThreePanelThingViewer
symbols.description: This control extends the sap.ui.ux3.ThingViewer control. The first panel can display a thing icon, a title, the Action Menu button, up to two rows of text descriptions (the first is wrapped, the second is truncated), vertical navigation bar (sap.suite.ui.commons.VerticalNavigationBar), and an image aka key visual. The second panel displays the header area as a vertical panel containing ThingGroup objects. The third panel is a main content area designed to display ThingGroup objects.

symbols.name: sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline
symbols.description:
The timeline control shows entries (such as objects, events, or posts) in chronological order.
A common use case is to provide information about changes to an object, or events related to an object. These entries can be generated by the system (for example, value XY changed from A to B), or added manually.
There are two distinct variants of the timeline: basic and social. The basic timeline is read-only, while the social timeline offers a high level of interaction and collaboration, and is integrated within SAP Jam.

properties.name: alignment
properties.description: Defines the alignment of timeline posts relative to the timeline axis. This option can be used for single-sided timelines only. If the axisOrientation property is set to Horizontal, the Right value is interpreted as bottom alignment and the Left value as top alignment.

properties.name: axisOrientation
properties.description: Defines the orientation of the timeline. Can be set to Vertical or Horizontal.

properties.name: data
properties.description: Data for the Timeline control.

deprecated.text: As of version 1.46, this property was replaced by JSONModel context binding.

properties.name: enableAllInFilterItem
properties.description: Enables to add 'All' at the beginning of the filter list.

deprecated.text: The filter list now includes a Select All check box, so the All radio button is no longer required. This property is ignored.

properties.name: enableBackendFilter
properties.description: Enables fetching data from backend instead of deriving filter values from the frontend values (displayed list). As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getEnableModelFilter}.

deprecated.text: Use the enableModelFilter property instead.

properties.name: enableBusyIndicator
properties.description: When this property is set to true, the timeline displays a busy indicator when loading data. This busy indicator blocks the interaction with the items until the data loading is complete. It is strongly recommended to use this option. Loading data without a busy indicator may confuse the users.

properties.name: enableDoubleSided
properties.description: If set to true, timeline posts are displayed on both sides of the timeline axis.

properties.name: enableModelFilter
properties.description: Enables filtering directly on the binding level. If set to true, all filters are translated into the filters in the model binding. When the OData model is used, the filtering is performed on the backend side. This option is strongly recommended. If set to false, all entries from the model need to be fetched before they can be filtered on the frontend side. Please be aware that the growingThreshold property determines how many entries can be rendered. Timeline requests all entries from the model before it performs the filtering. Some models may have internal limits for the number of entries that can be used in bindings. Such limits can be set using {@link sap.ui.model.Model#setSizeLimit}.

properties.name: enableScroll
properties.description: If set to true, the Timeline control has its own scroll bar, with the scrolling taking place within the Timeline control itself. Scrolling is required if you want to enable the lazyLoading property.

properties.name: enableSocial
properties.description: Adds a Reply link to the posts on a social timeline that allows users to reply to posts. When a user adds a reply, an event is fired. This event should be handled by external code.

properties.name: filterTitle
properties.description: Title for the data filter. When a filter is applied, this title is displayed in the message strip along with the filter name.

properties.name: forceGrowing
properties.description: If set to true, the Show More button is displayed when the user scrolls along the timeline axis.

properties.name: group
properties.description: Groups the timeline posts by year. As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getGroupByType}.

deprecated.text: Use the groupByType property instead.

properties.name: groupBy
properties.description: Groups the timeline posts by a field. Only fields that contain date values are supported.

properties.name: groupByType
properties.description: Groups the timeline posts by a time period, including year, quarter, month, week, and day. If set to None, no grouping is applied. If you specify a custom grouping function using the {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#setCustomGrouping} method, this function overrides the groupByType property settings.

properties.name: growing
properties.description: If set to true, the timeline displays a limited number of posts with a button to show more. The displayed posts limit can be set using the growingThreshold property. As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getGrowingThreshold}.

deprecated.text: Use the growingThreshold property instead, setting it to 0 to disable growing.

properties.name: growingThreshold
properties.description: Number of posts requested from the server at a time. Each time when the timeline needs to load more posts, it will request exactly this amount. The number of posts displayed in the timeline is increased by this number. If set to 0, all posts are fetched and displayed on the initial load.

properties.name: height
properties.description: Sets the height of the Timeline.

properties.name: lazyLoading
properties.description: Enables the Lazy Loading feature that automatically loads more posts as the user scrolls along the timeline axis. This feature works only when the enableScroll property is set to true. See also {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getEnableScroll}.

properties.name: noDataText
properties.description: This text is displayed when the control has no data. The default value is loaded from the component resource bundle.

properties.name: scrollingFadeout
properties.description: If set to Area, the timeline fades into the visible area margin. If set to AreaWithButtons, the timeline fades into the visible area margin and scroll buttons are displayed. If set to None, the fading effect is not applied. This feature works only when the enableScroll property is set to true. See also {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getEnableScroll}.

deprecated.text: Not Fiori.

properties.name: showFilterBar
properties.description:
Sets the visibility of the filter in the timeline toolbar.
As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getShowHeaderBar}.

deprecated.text: Use the showHeaderBar property instead.

properties.name: showHeaderBar
properties.description: Shows the timeline toolbar with search and filter options.

properties.name: showIcons
properties.description: Shows an icon on the timeline axis as an anchor for each entry node. If set to false, all icons are replaced by dots.

properties.name: showItemFilter
properties.description: Show item filter in filter area.

properties.name: showSearch
properties.description: Sets the search field visibility on the timeline toolbar.

properties.name: showSort
properties.description: Show sort icon in the header bar. For displaying this icon, sorting have to be allowed.

properties.name: showSuggestion
properties.description: If set to true, a suggest event is fired when the user enters text into the search field. Changing the suggestionItems aggregation in the suggest event listener will display suggestions inside a popup. As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.collaboration.components.feed.Component}.

deprecated.text: Use the Group Feed Component instead.

properties.name: showTimeFilter
properties.description: Shows the time range filter in the filter menu.

properties.name: sort
properties.description: Indicates whether the data should be sorted. If set to false the data model's default sorting is applied.

properties.name: dateTimePath
properties.description: Path for dateTime in mode binding. Use this property when you use factory function for TimeLineItem creation. When every item has different path or the datetime is calculated in factory sorting, filtering and searching has to be done manually using events. If not set for factory binding filter and sorting won't work.

properties.name: sortOldestFirst
properties.description: Whether the oldest item will be displayed first.

properties.name: textHeight
properties.description:
Height of the timeline posts. It can be set to either of the following types of values:
  • Automatic – If set to automatic, the optimal post height is calculated automatically to fit the timeline height specified by the height parameter. This option works only in horizontal timelines and only when the timeline height is defined. In vertical timelines, this setting is ignored.
  • Number – If set to a number, a corresponding number of text lines is displayed in every post.
  • Pixels – If set to a number followed by px, such as 50px, the closest number in lines is calculated and applied to the timeline posts, so that the post height corresponds to the specified number of pixels and the text lines are not cut off in the middle of a line.
  • Any other valid {@link sap.ui.core.CSSSize CSSSize} value that is inserted into the text wrapper without being changed.

properties.name: width
properties.description: Sets the width of the Timeline.

aggregations.name: content
aggregations.description: List of timeline posts.

aggregations.name: customFilter
aggregations.description: A custom filter to be used instead of the default item filter. This control must have an openBy or open function that is used by the timeline to open the control. If the control has both functions, openBy is used.

aggregations.name: filterList
aggregations.description: Custom filter criteria for the items filter.

aggregations.description: Items for suggestions. As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.collaboration.components.feed.Component}.

selectedItem.description: The first criteria selected in the filter criteria list (required for backward compatibility).

selectedItems.description: An array with all selected filter criteria.

timeKeys.name: timeKeys

clear.name: clear
clear.description: Is set to true when this event is fired by clearing the filter.

events.name: grow
events.description: This event is fired when the "More" button is clicked.

events.name: itemFiltering
events.description: This event is fired for every timeline post when data filtering is being applied. It indicates whether this post is included in the filtering and why. Can be used only when the enableModelFilter property is set to false.

item.name: item
item.description: Timeline post that is currently being filtered.

reasons.name: reasons
reasons.description: Reasons why the post is being filtered. Empty if the post is not being filtered. There are three properties available in the object: Search, Time, and Data. You can call preventDefault to the event object to prevent the result.

dataKeys.name: dataKeys
dataKeys.description: Array with keys used for data filtering.

timeKeys.name: timeKeys
timeKeys.description: An object specifying the start date (from) and the end date (to) of the time range.

searchTerm.name: searchTerm
searchTerm.description: The text string that has been typed into the search field.

events.name: select
events.description: This event is fired when a timeline post is selected.

selectedItem.name: selectedItem
selectedItem.description: The timeline post that is selected.

userAction.name: userAction
userAction.description:
Indicates whether the selection was triggered by a user action or in any other way.
Set to true if the selection was triggered by a user action, for example, by clicking with a mouse or pressing the Enter key.
Set to false if the selection was triggered in a different way, for example, by shifting focus back from a Popover element or by pressing an arrow key.
For backward compatibility, the select event is fired whenever an item gets focus.

events.name: suggest
events.description: This event is fired when the user enters text into the search field, in cases when the showSuggestion property is set to true. Changing the suggestionItems aggregation will show the suggestions inside a popup.

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getDateTimePath dateTimePath}. Path for dateTime in mode binding. Use this property when you use factory function for TimeLineItem creation. methods.name: getEnableBackendFilter

returnValue.description: Value of property enableBackendFilter

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableBackendFilter enableBackendFilter}. Enables fetching data from backend instead of deriving filter values from the frontend values (displayed list). As of version 1.46, replaced by {@link sap.suite.ui.commons.Timeline#getEnableModelFilter}. Default value is true.

deprecated.text: Use the enableModelFilter property instead.

methods.name: getEnableBusyIndicator

returnValue.description: Value of property enableBusyIndicator

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableBusyIndicator enableBusyIndicator}. When this property is set to true, the timeline displays a busy indicator when loading data. This busy indicator blocks the interaction with the items until the data loading is complete. It is strongly recommended to use this option. Loading data without a busy indicator may confuse the users. Default value is true.

methods.name: getEnableDoubleSided

returnValue.description: Value of property enableDoubleSided

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableDoubleSided enableDoubleSided}. If set to true, timeline posts are displayed on both sides of the timeline axis. Default value is false.

methods.name: getEnableModelFilter

returnValue.description: Value of property enableModelFilter

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableModelFilter enableModelFilter}. Enables filtering directly on the binding level. If set to true, all filters are translated into the filters in the model binding. When the OData model is used, the filtering is performed on the backend side. This option is strongly recommended. If set to false, all entries from the model need to be fetched before they can be filtered on the frontend side. Please be aware that the growingThreshold property determines how many entries can be rendered. Timeline requests all entries from the model before it performs the filtering. Some models may have internal limits for the number of entries that can be used in bindings. Such limits can be set using {@link sap.ui.model.Model#setSizeLimit}. Default value is true.

methods.name: getEnableScroll

returnValue.description: Value of property enableScroll

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableScroll enableScroll}. If set to true, the Timeline control has its own scroll bar, with the scrolling taking place within the Timeline control itself. Scrolling is required if you want to enable the lazyLoading property. Default value is true.

methods.name: getEnableSocial

returnValue.description: Value of property enableSocial

methods.description: Gets current value of property {@link #getEnableSocial enableSocial}. Adds a Reply link to the posts on a social timeline that allows users to reply to posts. When a user adds a reply, an event is fired. This event should be handled by external code. Default value is false.
